Added a MuPDFFragment fragment that uses your custom parent activity intent to get the arguments.
Usage
- axml: <fragment android:name="com.artifex.mupdfdemo.MuPDFFragment" ... />
- csharp: var intent = new Intent(this, typeof(YourActivityThatUseTheMuPDFFragment)); intent.SetAction(Intent.ActionView); intent.SetData(Uri.Parse("/sdcard/Download/file.pdf")); // pdf path intent.PutExtra("DisableButtons", true); // hide the top toolbar completely or not StartActivity(intent);
The compiled MuPDF native library does not support arm64, so please disable arm64 support in your Android project.

FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes:
PM> Install-Package Microsoft.AspNet.Identity.Samples -Pre
remove from packages file Install-Package Microsoft.AspNet.Identity.Samples
PM> Uninstall-Package Microsoft.AspNet.Identity.EntityFramework
PM> Uninstall-Package EntityFramework
and remove this from web.config:
<entityFramework> <defaultConnectionFactory type="System.Data.Entity.Infrastructure.LocalDbConnectionFactory, EntityFramework"> <parameters> <parameter value="v11.0" /> </parameters> </defaultConnectionFactory> <providers> <provider invariantName="System.Data.SqlClient" type="System.Data.Entity.SqlServer.SqlProviderServices, EntityFramework.SqlServer" /> </providers> </entityFramework>
and
<configSections>
<section name="entityFramework" type="System.Data.Entity.Internal.ConfigFile.EntityFrameworkSection, EntityFramework, Version=6.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b77a5c561934e089" requirePermission="false" /> </configSections>
and
<connectionStrings> <add name="DefaultConnection" connectionString="Data Source=(LocalDb)\v11.0;Initial Catalog=testidentitystuff-2-1-alpha1;Integrated Security=SSPI" providerName="System.Data.SqlClient" /> </connectionStrings>
delete IdentityModels.cs from models folder
delete IdentityConfig.cs from App_Start folder
add in web.config replace:
<connectionStrings> <add name="EgoDB" connectionString="Database=MyEgoDB;Root=C:\Users\dom\Desktop\EGO-DB" /> </connectionStrings>

FeedPackage.Description:
A library that makes it easier to persist and apply stored application state (window locations and sizes, user settings and preferences, etc).
Instead of moving data back and forth from a .settings file, just specify which properties of which objects need to be persistent (in one of several ways), and you're already done.
Even though the library is tiny (<1000 LOC) it means serious business, it's powerful, highly customizable and provides many extension points, but comes with all the basic functionality built in.
The source repository is on github, and there is an article describing it on codeproject (check the project url). The article is a bit dated compared to the library code though.

FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes:
- JavaScript and CSS manager configuration has been integrated into regular Web.config infrastructure.
- New globalization string resource approach (check documentation on http://calipso.codeplex.com about string localization).
- Some fixes on JavaScript and CSS manager (design decisions now enhanced or replaced by better ones).
- jQuery is still a mandatory dependency, but Calipso requires it as a reference and it's not included in official distribution. That's it's mandatory to add a JavaScript include in Calipso.config <javascriptManager> element. This is better as newer jQuery version can be plugged in Calipso without waiting for a new Calipso release.
- Now JavaScript script tags are still rendered in the ordered on which scripts were added as references in the server side, but references having an identifier starting with "Dependency//" (case insensitive) are rendered first, later the rest. Resources are rendered just after dependencies.
- Client-side JavaScript PageContext, PageManager objects and base Control class are now available through shortcut variables: $calipso$context, $calipso$manager and $calipso$control. Full namespace paths are still fine and this won't change in the future. It's just for make things easier.
For more details and how-tos, please visit Calipso's official page on Codeplex http://calipso.codeplex.com

-> Works on top of new and existing Web Forms applications, allowing the creation of mixed server and client-side server controls using Web standards.
-> State-of-the-art, exclusive way of working with CSS and JavaScript dependencies!
-> Light-weight client-side JavaScript dependencies.
-> Build and run-time CSS and JavaScript combination and minification.
-> Unobstructive component-oriented UI programming in the client-side using pure JavaScript and jQuery.
-> True object-oriented approach both on client and server side!
-> Decent and rich event-oriented initialization that makes things easier to get done right.
-> Pure CSS theming support.
FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes:
- JavaScript and CSS manager configuration has been integrated into regular Web.config infrastructure.
- Now JavaScript and CSS manager support the concept of "standalone reference". This means that such kind of references won't get combined with others, rendering a standalone script tag in the whole page.
- Theming. Calipso introduces a theming approach. Learn more on http://calipso.codeplex.com!
- New globalization string resource approach (check documentation on http://calipso.codeplex.com about string localization).
- Some fixes on JavaScript and CSS manager (design decisions now enhanced or replaced by better ones).
- jQuery is still a mandatory dependency, but Calipso requires it as a reference and it's not included in official distribution. That's it's mandatory to add a JavaScript include in Calipso.config <javascriptManager> element. This is better as newer jQuery version can be plugged in Calipso without waiting for a new Calipso release.
- Now JavaScript script tags are still rendered in the ordered on which scripts were added as references in the server side, but references having an identifier starting with "Dependency//" (case insensitive) are rendered first, later the rest. Resources are rendered just after dependencies.
- Client-side JavaScript PageContext, PageManager objects and base Control class are now available through shortcut variables: $calipso$context, $calipso$manager and $calipso$control. Full namespace paths are still fine and this won't change in the future. It's just for make things easier.
- Lot of fixes on JavaScriptManager and CssManager, specially when those work on non-debug compilation mode (release mode on Web.config).
For more details and how-tos, please visit Calipso's official page on Codeplex http://calipso.codeplex.com
